# Lesson 1.1: Business Classifications

## Topic Overview

Introductory lesson on business types: profit, non-profit, and cooperatives; classification by size according to Istat and by economic sector. Explores legal forms (sole proprietorship, partnerships, corporations, cooperatives), asset liability, share capital, quotas, and shareholder rights. Compares LLCs (SRL), Joint-Stock Companies (SPA), Limited Partnerships with Shares (SAPA), General Partnerships (SNC), Limited Partnerships (SAS), and family businesses, illustrating requirements, governance, constraints, and criteria for choosing the most suitable form based on risk, size, resources, and activity.

---

## Key Points Summary

1. Classification of businesses by objective: profit-oriented (production companies), non-profit (service/consumption companies), cooperatives (mutualistic companies)
2. Profit-oriented businesses: aimed at producing goods/services and generating economic value; objective to maximize economic value and generate profit to remunerate owners' investment
3. Non-profit businesses: explicit constraint not to distribute profits to owners; objective to satisfy human/foundational needs; profits reinvested in the business
4. Cooperative societies/mutualistic companies: produce goods/services primarily for members at more advantageous conditions; profits distributed among members
5. Possibility of profit in non-profits and cooperatives: defined as difference between revenues and costs; in non-profits not distributable to owners, in cooperatives distributable to members
6. Classification by size (employees according to Istat): micro 0–9; small 10–49; medium 50–249; large >250; possible presence of thousands of employees in large companies
7. Course focus: predominantly on large for-profit companies; many considerations also applicable to small and medium companies with adjustments
8. Classification by sector: primary (agriculture, extractive, fishing); secondary (industry, construction); tertiary (services: commercial, transport, credit, insurance); advanced tertiary (culture, education, advanced services based on knowledge/ingenuity)
9. Classification by legal form: individual and collective businesses; collective: profit companies vs. mutualistic companies
10. Profit companies: partnerships vs. corporations; key difference in ultimate responsibility for business risk

**Key Quote:**
> "As business risk increases, it is preferable for partners to protect their personal assets by choosing a corporate legal form."

