## Classification of Businesses by Objective

Businesses are distinguished by the objective pursued into three categories: profit-oriented (production companies), non-profit (service/consumption companies), and cooperatives (mutualistic companies). The former aim at maximizing economic value and generating profit to remunerate owners. Non-profits have constraints that prevent profit distribution to owners and pursue the satisfaction of human or foundational needs; any profits are reinvested. Cooperatives produce goods and services primarily for members at more advantageous conditions than the market and can distribute profits to members.

**Key Points:**
- **Profit-oriented:** production of goods/services and maximization of economic value
- **Non-profit:** prohibition on distributing profits to owners; profits reinvested
- **Cooperatives:** priority to members; more advantageous conditions; profits distributable to members
- All can generate profit as the difference between revenues and costs

**Explanation:**
The instructor introduces the distinction explaining how the objective influences governance, profit distribution, and target beneficiaries. Emphasizes that the course focuses mainly on for-profit companies, while maintaining relevance across other types.

**Considerations:**
- Verify the existence of constraints on profit distribution in non-profits
- In cooperatives, define objective criteria for more advantageous conditions for members

**Special Circumstances:**
- If a non-profit generates profits, how should they be managed? They must be reinvested in the entity, not distributed to owners
- If a cooperative generates profits, how to distribute them? In proportion to statutory rules and members' quotas

