## Shareholder Rights

Shareholders hold various rights towards the company: a) profit distribution (dividends) proportional to shares owned; b) pre-emptive right in new share issues to avoid dilution of share capital; c) participation in voting at meetings with weight proportional to number of shares held; d) right of withdrawal if the company changes its corporate purpose or other essential characteristics of the activity.

**Key Points:**
- Dividends proportional to quota (e.g.: 60 shares out of 100 → 60%)
- Pre-emptive right on new issues
- Voting proportional to number of shares
- Withdrawal in case of essential changes to corporate purpose

**Explanation:**
The instructor repeatedly emphasizes the 60% example to clarify economic and governance proportionality, and the role of pre-emptive right against dilution.

**Example:**
Company with 100 shares of €1,000. A partner with 60 shares receives 60% of distributed dividends and holds 60% of voting power at meetings.

**Considerations:**
- Clearly define withdrawal conditions in bylaws
- Manage timing and methods of pre-emptive offering

**Special Circumstances:**
- If pre-emptive offering to shareholders is omitted, how to avoid litigation? Comply with legal terms or provide statutory compensation

